50|$|In HeroQuest {{players do}} not compare the numbers thrown, but instead compare the implied results. Results rank from fumble through failure and success to critical. A success is scored if the <b>die</b> <b>roll</b> does {{not exceed the}} ability score, with a 1 {{indicating}} a critical success. If the <b>die</b> <b>roll</b> exceeds the ability score, {{the result is a}} failure, while a 20 indicates a fumble (critical failure).|$|E
25|$|However, chance plays a {{large role}} in Button Men; it is always {{possible}} for a 20-sided <b>die</b> to <b>roll</b> a 1 at an inopportune time. Among tournament legal buttons, at least, no match-up is impossible for either side to win. Inevitably it happens that a weaker Button Man or a less skilled player will claim some improbable victories due to lucky <b>die</b> <b>rolls.</b> This effect is offset somewhat, however, by the rule that a player must win three rounds to win a game.|$|R
